.TH "NFTFWAN" "1" "" "" "Nftfw documentation"
.SH NAME
\f[B]nftfwan\f[R] \[em] command line tool to analyse the counters
installed by \f[B]nftfw\f[R] into \f[B]nftables\f[R]
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]nftfwan\f[R] [\f[B]\-h\f[R]] [\f[B]\-f\f[R] \f[I]FILE\f[R]]
[\f[B]\-4 |\-6 | \-u | \-p | \-r | \-n \f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]nftfwan\f[R] is a command line tool that reads the some of counters
from the \f[B]nftfw\f[R] firewall running in \f[B]nftables\f[R].
This data is provided by \f[B]nftfables\f[R] in JSON format and requires
parsing to obtain the counters.
\f[B]nftfwan\f[R] needs to be run by the super user to have the
necessary permission to read the data.
.PP
The aim of \f[B]nftfwan\f[R] is to get a measure of what is happening to
the inbound connections to the system.
It gives an overall view of the type of traffic a system is subjected
to, how much of that traffic is blocked by the firewall systems, how
much is filtered into the applications with open ports, and how much is
simply ignored.
The script is not `general purpose', it uses knowledge of the flow of
packets through the firewall provided with the \f[B]nftfw\f[R] system
and may not provide correct numbers if this flow is changed.
.PP
The script reads the data from the kernel and outputs two tables, that
are `pretty printed'.
The first shows `Usage', the general flow through the firewall, the
numbers are computed from the counts of packets entering a particular
filter.
The rows named in the first column and are:
.IP \[bu] 2
IP Connects \- the number of external IP connects
.IP \[bu] 2
Whitelist \- the number of connects that have been accepted for
whitelisting
.IP \[bu] 2
Blacknets \- the number of connects that have been rejected by the
\f[I]blacknets\f[R] system
.IP \[bu] 2
Blacklist \- the number of connects that have been rejected by the
\f[I]blacklist\f[R] system
.IP \[bu] 2
To firewall \- the number of connects that have been passed into the
\f[I]incoming\f[R] chain, looking for matches with specified ports
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[I]Firewall processing\f[R] \- a separator to mark that the rows below
are taken from the \f[I]incoming\f[R] chain and the total used for
percentages changes
.IP \[bu] 2
Accepted packets \- how many connections have been accepted for
processing by the filter in \f[I]incoming\f[R]
.IP \[bu] 2
Dropped packets \- how may connections didn\[cq]t find a destination in
\f[I]incoming\f[R]
.PP
The second table `Service' breaks down accepted connections in
\f[I]incoming\f[R] by service type.
The first column shows the service name if it is shown if the port
number appears in the standard \f[I]/etc/services\f[R] file on the
system., otherwise the port number is displayed.
.PP
Both tables show numbers for IPv4, IPv6 and a total in subsequent
columns.
Arguments to the script can reduce the columns that are displayed.
.SS Options
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\-\-help\f[R]
Prints brief usage information.
.TP
\f[B]\-4\f[R], \f[B]\-\-ip\f[R]
Restrict output to IPv4
.TP
\f[B]\-6\f[R], \f[B]\-\-ip6\f[R]
Restrict output to IPv6
.TP
\f[B]\-u \f[R], \f[B]\-\-usage\f[R]
Only output usage information
.TP
\f[B]\-p \f[R], \f[B]\-\-ports\f[R]
Only output port information
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\-\-noborders\f[R]
Don\[cq]t print borders to the tables
.TP
\f[B]\-r\f[R], \f[B]\-\-raw\f[R]
Print decoded data from the kernel and exit.
Prints IPv4 and IPv6 unless \-4 or \-6 is included.
This is a debugging aid.
.TP
\f[B]\-f \f[R], \f[B]\-\-file\f[R] FILE
Read data from the file.
This is a debugging aid.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[I]/etc/nftfw\f[R] or \f[I]/usr/local/etc/nftfw\f[R]
Location of control files
.TP
\f[I]/var/lib/nftfw/\f[R] or \f[I]/usr/local/var/lib/nftfw\f[R]
Location of \f[I]build\f[R], \f[I]install\f[R], lock file and sqlite3
database storing file positions and blacklist information
